{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"68b9681c-02f9-40dd-92a4-8b8605adbb25","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use **lifecycle event mappings** in your `MauiProgram.cs` (or app startup) via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs when activity is pausing\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs when activity is no longer visible\n        }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // runs when the app enters background\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add the `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` namespace.\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code compilable on each target.\n- Each platform exposes its native events (e.g., `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, `WillTerminate`, etc.) through the same fluent API.\n- This is configured once in `CreateMauiApp()` alongside your other builder setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b50ce0a-d486-4825-bc5f-b1c63225c0a7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development that I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":392,"requestId":"4833:1A5086:75F3D17:824542C:69F3FB0B"},"id":"df2cf0b8-9300-4b23-b975-b279441ff121","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:00:04.080Z","parentId":"70eb4da0-6da9-4134-a124-2a0e45d4d0dd"}
